The man upon whom the concentrated hate of radicalism has been
so long directed & for whose deposition the pretended voice
of the nation so angrily shrieked holds his own & will continue
to hold it to the end of his term. All honest men & true
patriots are jubilant & full of glory at the result while the
impeachers are down, down in the dust of disarray, depression
and degradation. The sword & the shadow of disaster & disgrace
has fallen upon them & their great fabric of gilded hopes, just
as it reached its pinacle of completion, has been shattered,
The entire structure has tumbled down with a crash & the
elaborate work of Old Thad & his train of devilish contenders
lies there, an almost indistinguishable mass of ruins-- none
but Radicals can realize the vast cubic measure, the length
breadth and thickness of the calamity that has befallen this
standstill-- to a fearful pause just as it was rushing blindly,
madly on the framework of the government-- just as it had poised
itself to deal the fatal blow by hurling from power the Executive
of the Nation-- when friends of Constitutional liberty were
trembling for its safety-- just at this juncture the Providence
which guides the destiny of Nations interposed & saved us from
impending ruin.

Captain William Armstrong rode past a Confederate soldier propped
against a tree. Shortly he decided to go back and see if the
soldier needed any help. There he found his older brother
Alfred, very sick with typhoid. As the Yankees held Winchester,
william persuaded them to pass Alfred through the lines to a
hospital where he died and was buried 29 July 1864. After the
war William went by train to Winchester and brought Alfred's
body back to Stony Point to be buried at New Providence Cemetery.
